Final Project: Spotify Data Analysis¶

Name: Jordan Vanderwolf

Introduction¶

I am running analysis on spotify song data. This database downloaded from Kagle link: https://www.kaggle.com/pepepython/spotify-huge-database-daily-charts-over-3-years. The data is a amalgomation of Spotify's Rancking Charts for 3 years. The charts are by countries so a song can appear multiple times if it ranked in many countries charts. Each row is a equivlaent to a song that appeared on the chart. The rows contain many values but ones I want to focus on are country that contains the chart, the song name, artist, popularity of the song, if it was a single or part of an album, genre, aritst, release date, followers, danceability, Energy, Key, Loudness, Mode, Speechiness, Acousticness, Instrumentalness, Liveness, Valence, Temp, and Duration. For more information on these stats, head to the dataset link. The popularity was calculated by the duration the song stayed on the chart and what rankings it attained. The music features columns are calculated by spotify in there spotipy utility. For more information about spotipy, use this link: https://spotipy.readthedocs.io/en/2.18.0/.

I am interested in many questions that this dataset could procide insight on but I want to know specifically what makes a song popular. i also want to explore how music has change over the years. Using these values I hope to explore this train of thought.

Tidying the Data¶

I will not make any use of the uri column as it does not pertain to any data. There are two genre columns. There are columns that list the track number in album and the number of tracks in its album, and its explicit label, which I do not deem useful for the popularity analysis I want to run. The genre_new column is the dataset's author improved genre column. Therefore, I will also not be using genre column. I will remove these columns to tidy the data.

spotify1 = spotify.drop(['Uri', 'Genre', 'Track_number', 'Tracks_in_album'], axis=1)

I will keep the artist column in case I want to run data on the Artist_following column. I will get rid of album and title.

In [60]:
numerical_features = ['Artist_followers','key','loudness','mode','danceability', 'energy', 'instrumentalness', 'valence', 'liveliness', 'speechiness', 'acoustics',
                      'speechiness', 'acoustics', 'instrumentalness', 'liveliness', 'valence', 'tempo', 'duration_ms', 
                      'time_signature']

spotify1[numerical_features] = spotify1[numerical_features].apply(pd.to_numeric)

#convert explicit column to integer represting 0: False, 1: True

d = {'True': 1, 'False': 0, 'single':0, 'album':1, 'compilation':1}
spotify1['Explicit'] = spotify1['Explicit'].map(d)
spotify1['Album/Single'] = spotify1['Album/Single'].map(d)
#rename column Album/Single so we dont have to worry about the /
spotify1 = spotify1.rename(columns={'Album/Single':'is_single'})

EDA¶

EDA, or exploratory analysis means that we are trying to provide visualization to the data so we can gain some insight on it. For more infromation on types of EDA you can use, follow this link: https://towardsdatascience.com/exploratory-data-analysis-eda-python-87178e35b14

We will first be Using a correlation matrix heat map to analyse correlation between columns. This will help us identify what columns we want to use for the popularity analysis. For more information on how to customisize your heatmap use these links: https://towardsdatascience.com/annotated-heatmaps-in-5-simple-steps-cc2a0660a27d, https://heartbeat.fritz.ai/seaborn-heatmaps-13-ways-to-customize-correlation-matrix-visualizations-f1c49c816f07 .

Judging from this plot, none of the variables seem to be highly correlated with popularity. The two best predictors of popularity are whether its a single, the artist's followers, danceability, and loudness with around 0.1 correlation.

From the plot you can see that there is a little better results with year. Explicitness, danceability, and speechiness all have a correlation of 0.2.

The most high cordinated columns are loudness and energy. This means as songs get more loud they increase energy.

Another interesting question is what makes a song danceable? From this it seems it is valence, speechiness, and explicitness, since they have the highest correlation to the dancibility column.

Hypothesis Testing¶

I want to see for sure if there is a correlation between the musical features of a song. When Hypothesis testing we will use the null hypothesis, which is that the variables do not correlate to Popularity. If we are given p values < 0.05, I will reject the null hypothesis.

To use logit, the target must have values between 0 and 1. I will create a new column that encodes the Popularity column into a value between 0 and 1 by using the formula curr_value - values' minimum / values' maximum. This will give us that relative encoding

In [73]:
spotify1['pop_encoding'] = (spotify1['Popularity'] - spotify1['Popularity'].min())/spotify1['Popularity'].max()
spotify1.head()

I will show you a different approach using a linerar regression model this time, using OLS.

First we just get the numerical data of spotify1 so we can run the stats model on all the variables. Then we seperate out the dependent variable as the target and make all other variables the features, which will act as predictors

Machine Learning¶

Now we are trying to create a machine learning component that can successfully predict Popularity from the cariables we deemed significant above. I will be using linear regression model since our target variable is continous meaning that it is a range of values as opposed to a binary variable that contains only 2 values.

We will standardize data across all features along and axis.

In [80]:
#Standardizing numerical data
features = preprocessing.scale(features)
In [81]:
X, y = features, target
X.shape, y.shape
Out[81]:
((170573, 14), (170573, 1))

The train-test split procedure is used to estimate the performance of machine learning algorithms when they are used to make predictions on data not used to train the model. This means we will take our data and split it into training groups and testing groups. The training group will be used to calculate the linear regression model. The test group will be used to find the accuracy of that model

In [82]:
#spliting the data using train_test_split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.4, random_state=0)
In [83]:
#finding the linear regression only on the training data
lin_reg = LinearRegression().fit(X_train, y_train)
In [84]:
predictions = lin_reg.predict(X_test)
In [85]:
# This tests how well the X test data would predict the Y test result
lin_reg.score(X_test, y_test)

We will use a 10 fold Cross Validation. K-fold cross validation is a procedure used to estimate the skill of the model on new data. This means we split the data into 10 groups, evaluate the the score of how well each group predicted the target value.

Conclusion¶

With this tutorial, we analysed popularity of music tracks with relation to musical features, such as dancibility, explicitness, energy, key, loudness, mode, speechiness, acoustics, instrumentalness, liveliness, valence, and tempo. We know that these variables are related now. We can use this analysis to predict how popular a track will become based off of its features. This could be very useful for record companies who want to optimize their song popularity. It is also useful for spotify if they want to track how new songs might perform and so they should reccomend that song.
